raw_response:
The code is already following the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP). This principle states that "Clients should not be forced to depend on interfaces they do not use." In this case, each class implements only the methods it needs. 

However, if we look at the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), there is a violation in BasicPrinter and AdvancedPrinter classes as they have more than one responsibility: printing documents, scanning documents, and faxing. This means that these classes are doing too many things. If you need to change how these printers behave, it would be better if each class had only one job (printing, scanning or faxing).

To refactor this code according to SRP:
```java
public interface Printer {
    void print(String document);
}

public interface Scanner {
    void scan();
}

public interface FaxMachine {
    void fax(String recipient);
}

// BasicPrinter class now only implements the Printer interface.
public class BasicPrinter implements Printer  {
	...
}

// AdvancedPrinter class now only implements the Printer and Scanner interfaces.
public class AdvancedPrinter implements Printer, Scanner {
	...
}

// SmartPhone class now only implements the Scanner and FaxMachine interfaces.
public class SmartPhone implements Scanner, FaxMachine {
	...
}
```
This way each class has a single responsibility which makes it easier to maintain and extend in future. 

Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) is not violated here as all classes are substitutable for their interfaces without causing any issues. The SmartPhone can be used wherever an object of type Scanner or FaxMachine is expected, which it fulfills.

