The violation in this code is Interface Segregation Principle (ISP). The Vehicle interface has too many methods, and each class implementing the Vehicle interface is forced to implement methods it doesn't use. 

To refactor the code to comply with ISP, we can split the Vehicle interface into smaller interfaces that are more specific:

```java
interface Drivable {
    void start();
    void stop();
    void drive();
}

interface Flyable {
    void fly();
}

interface Diveable {
    void dive();
}

class Car implements Drivable  {
     @Override
     public void start()  {
         System.out.println("Car started.");
     }

     @Override
     public void stop()  {
         System.out.println("Car stopped.");
     }

     @Override
     public void drive()  {
         System.out.println("Car is driving on the road.");
     }
}

class Plane implements Flyable  {
    @Override
    public void fly()  {
        System.out.println("Plane is flying.");
    }
}

class Submarine implements Diveable  {
    @Override
    public void dive()  {
        System.out.println("Submarine is diving.");
    }
}
```
This way, each class only has to implement the methods it needs and doesn't have to implement methods it won't use. This adheres more closely to ISP than the original code.

