raw_response:
The violation in this code is the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP). The classes `NotificationSender` and `NotificationReceiver` are responsible for sending and receiving notifications, respectively. This violates SRP as each class has more than one reason to change - it can send or receive a notification.

To refactor this code to comply with the Single Responsibility Principle:

```kotlin
interface Notification {
    val type: String
}

data class Email(override val type: String = "email", val recipient: String, val subject: String, val body: String) : Notification
data class SMS(override val type: String = "sms", val phoneNumber: String, val message: String) : Notification
data class PushNotification(override val type: String = "push notification", val deviceId: String, val title: String, val message: String) : Notification
data class SlackMessage(override val type: String = "slack message", val channel: String, val message: String) : Notification

interface Notifier {
    fun sendNotification(notification: Notification)
}

class EmailService : Notifier {
    override fun sendNotification(email: Email)  {
        println("Sending email to ${email.recipient} with subject: ${email.subject}")
    }
}

class SMSService : Notifier {
    override fun sendNotification(sms: SMS)  {
        println("Sending SMS to ${sms.phoneNumber}: ${sms.message}")
    }
}

interface Receiver {
    fun receiveNotification(notification: Notification)
}

class EmailClient : Receiver {
    override fun receiveNotification(email: Email)  {
        println("Received email from ${email.recipient} with subject: ${email.subject}")
    }
}
```
In this refactored code, `Email`, `SMS`, etc., are data classes representing different types of notifications. The `Notifier` interface has a method for sending any type of notification and the `Receiver` interface has a method for receiving any type of notification. This way, each class is responsible only for one thing - either sending or receiving notifications.

