To fix this issue, we should make the content field private in the Resume class and provide getter/setter methods for it:

```csharp
public class Resume
{
    public string Content {get; set;}

    public Resume(string content)
    {
        this.Content = content;
    }
}
```
This change does not directly violate any SOLID principle, but it is a good practice to follow when designing classes in C#. 

As for the other part of your question, there are no direct SOLID principles violations in this code as per my understanding. The interfaces (PortalUser) and their implementations (JobSeeker, Recruiter, Administrator) adhere to the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), Open-Closed Principle (OCP), Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP), and Interface Segregation Principle (ISP).

