The violation in this code is the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP). The SRP states that a class should have only one reason to change, meaning it should have only one job or responsibility. 

In your case, all classes except `LightBulb` and `DeviceControl` are doing more than one thing: they're implementing an interface which is not just for turning on/off but also controlling volume and locking the device. This goes against the Single Responsibility Principle as each class has multiple responsibilities.

To refactor this code to comply with SRP, we could split these classes into smaller ones that have a single responsibility:

```csharp
public interface IDeviceControl
{
    void TurnOn();
    void TurnOff();
}

public interface IVolumeControl
{
    void VolumeUp();
    void VolumeDown();
}

public interface ILockable
{
    void Lock();
}
```
Then, we can implement these interfaces in the classes that need them:

```csharp
public class LightBulb : IDeviceControl
{
    // ...
}

public class RegularLightBulb : LightBulb, IDeviceControl, IVolumeControl, ILockable
{
    // ...
}

public class RGBLightBulb : LightBulb, IDeviceControl, IVolumeControl, ILockable
{
    // ...
}
```
This way, each class has only one responsibility and is easier to maintain. 

Please note that this refactoring does not change the functionality of your code but it makes it more manageable by separating responsibilities into different interfaces. The actual behavior of the devices (turning on/off, changing volume etc.) remains unchanged.

